1651 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEARTS OF L.A. / HOW THE QUAKE ROCKED OUR SPIRITS AND CHANGED OUR LIVES; TAKING 
CHARGE; 'WE SAW A LOT OF DESTRUCTION. WE KNEW THERE HAD BEEN DEATH.' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Lt. Dan Hoffman, Hoffman, 42, Los Angeles Police Department, Devonshire 
Division Daywatch Watch Commander, resides in Thousand Oaks with his wife and 
three sons. He is a 20-year veteran of LAPD. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I run the football program out at T.O. (Thousand Oaks), and we had one of the 
people on the board over for dinner that night with her son. The kids were 
playing outside about 8 o'clock in the evening, and they tell us, "Hey, there's 
a weird wind out here, dad. If you stand right here you can feel hot air." We 
shined 'em. 
</P>
<P>
 When the guests were leaving at 9 o'clock, all three of my sons and this other 
boy, Sean, said, "You've got to come out here and feel it," so we did. Me, my 
wife and the boy's mother went over to the area where the boys told us to stand 
and, by God, you could feel hot air coming.  
</P>
<P>
 The wind was blowing in a southern direction. It was like a gulf stream of air 
that was blowing down onto our front porch area. I thought it was crazy, but 
when they got me out there, it was happening. So, when we got back in the house 
that night, my two little ones insisted -- which was unusual -- on sleeping 
with their older brother after this incident. It scared them. They were down on 
the bottom floor, and my wife and I were on the second floor. 
</P>
<P>
 For whatever reason, I woke up at 4:27. I have a clock right by my head. And I 
was wondering how many minutes before my alarm goes off. Usually for a workday, 
I get up at 5:30. I had kicked the covers off me and I was pulling them on me 
and rolling around and looking at the ceiling when the earthquake hit. 
</P>
<P>
 It was a violent earthquake. I lived in Van Nuys when we had the '71 
earthquake. Immediately, my mind flashed back to 1971. It was a real violent, 
direct hitting, solid shaking (earthquake), as opposed to '71. I remember back 
at my dad's house and opening the door to my room and standing out in the back 
yard and I could see the patio and the wall doing a wave. This one was 
completely different. This one was quick, violent, sustained, as if someone was 
hitting you with an uppercut. Just pounding the foundation of the house. 
</P>
<P>
 It's like "The Exorcist." The bed in my bedroom was literally lifting off the 
ground and smacking into the floor and everything was shaking around me. 
</P>
<P>
 My wife woke up and she started screaming, "Oh, my God!" For whatever reason, 
she ended up at the end of the bed and was kind of like huddling on the end of 
the bed. I was grabbing the headboard. Then the thing stopped, and I yelled 
down to the kids. By now, my little one, Patrick, was screaming, "Dad! Dad! 
What's wrong?" So, I went downstairs. We got them all together. 
</P>
<P>
 My father passed away in November. My mother and father lived about a mile and 
a half away from me. My mom now lives there by herself. She had never lived by 
herself. So, I told the family, "Get the flashlights going, and all of you just 
stay in the family room. I'm going to be back. I've got to get to my mom." 
</P>
<P>
 I went to my car, and the thing that struck me was the eeriness. Everything 
was totally dark. I remember thinking the headlights on my car weren't doing 
the job because I'm used to more light. There was no power. So when I got to my 
mom's, I pulled my car onto the front of her lawn and lit up the front of her 
house. 
</P>
<P>
 The neighbor next door yelled at me, "Are you checking on her?" I said yes. 
So, I banged on the door and got my mom. I opened the door and she was visibly 
shaking. I just said, "Let's go. You're coming with me." 
</P>
<P>
 When I got back to my house, I got the flashlight, checking for damage, and 
told my wife, "As soon as I'm done here, I'm going into work." I got the radio 
going and I knew we had been hit hard in the West San Fernando Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 As I'm coming into the station, I wonder if I can handle the news media in the 
lobby, because I knew they were going to be here, but when I got here they 
weren't here. They were out at the train derailment, Northridge mall, gas main 
blowup. 
</P>
<P>
 I walked into the station, and it was on its knees. Total bedlam. Everything 
was tipped over. You couldn't walk without having to step over file cabinets, 
desks. The walls were cracked. The ceiling panels were on the ground. The 
lights were out. There was so much destruction here that when they set up the 
CP (command post), they couldn't get into the room where we keep our radios. It 
took them an hour and 15 minutes to clear the debris away. 
</P>
<P>
 When I walked in, everything was on the ground. This place was trashed. 
Shotguns. Everything was trashed. Morning watch is not what you would call a 
heavily deployed watch, so I knew there weren't a lot of people working.  
</P>
<P>
 I was operations lieutenant, which meant I was in charge of all units, where 
they were going, what their assignments are to be. Making all the necessary 
liaisons with building and safety. It's almost like a blur now that I think 
about it.  
</P>
<P>
 You immediately do a roll call of officers right over the air to see if 
they're OK, and Jim (Lt. Jim Cansler) had done that, which really impressed me. 
Now, we know what our force is. Then I assigned people to call everyone at home 
and tell them to get in. 
</P>
<P>
 . . . (As supervisors) we are trained in an earthquake situation to delegate, 
assign, monitor and make telephone calls. The officers in the field do the 
assessments, and the assessments were coming in. Right away, we knew about the 
9500 block of Reseda (Northridge Meadows apartments). We knew that a 
three-story apartment building was now a two-story apartment building. The Fire 
Department was on scene, and we knew it was bad.  
</P>
<P>
 The other thing that we had was the train derailment at Nordhoff and Tampa. We 
knew there were hazardous chemicals on the train. So, that was a whole other 
major problem; you have the evacuation process, (have to) close down traffic 
lanes. We knew the Northridge college campus had sustained a big hit and that 
the newly built parking structure had completely collapsed and that the science 
building was on fire, and the Fire Department told us hazardous chemicals had 
combined and are burning into the sky.  
</P>
<P>
 We knew Northridge Mall had been totally demolished. And, of course, we had 
citizens coming in. We knew we had single-family residences out there and there 
was a lot of damage. I personally thought there were going to be a lot of 
injuries and we were going to see lots of deaths, based on how violent this 
thing had been and the damage I had seen. We knew there were other apartment 
buildings out there that were just as demolished and uninhabitable. You could 
just look down Reseda (Boulevard) and see it. 
</P>
<P>
 We found out fairly soon that we lost one of our motor officers. He was a 
traffic motor officer assigned to the Valley Bureau. We got the word . . . that 
he had gone off the end of the freeway and then it was like, "My God, we're cut 
off from everybody." 
</P>
<P>
 We had Balboa and Rinaldi where that gas vent was on fire, where Clinton 
visited. That was in our division too. We had houses on fire . . . and we knew 
it. On top of all this, the traffic signals weren't working. And then you had 
everybody in the United States calling asking, "Is my son OK? Is my mother OK?" 
And we didn't have the manpower to do it at that point. For two days, we were 
basically telling them, "We can't do anything for you," but then we were able 
to take the light-duty officers and they became our welfare check cars, so we 
were able to start doing that. 
</P>
<P>
 I went out and assessed the damage with Capt. Vance Proctor. We went to the 
Northridge Meadows apartments, the Northridge mall and Cal State Northridge. We 
saw a lot of destruction. We knew there had been death. I'm surprised there 
wasn't more. 
</P>
<P>
 A lot of our officers came in on their own, officers who lost just as much as 
these people. Some in Santa Clarita were stranded. But we had officers who live 
in this division who came into work and told us their homes had been lost. 
</P>
<P>
 At the station, we didn't have any water. We were running off a generator. You 
have to feed your people. Gas the cars. All these things become huge problems. 
We had food delivered. We had water trucks brought over here. Gasoline was 
delivered. You couldn't flush the toilets, so we had outhouses delivered. Then, 
of course, you've got rescue operations and seeing families without food and 
water. We had officers come in, load up their cars and take it out to them. 
</P>
<P>
 We'd load them up four bodies (officers) to a car at a time. You wouldn't see 
them for six hours. You knew they were there doing a job. 
</P>
<P>
 I wanted a flush toilet real bad. Hot water. A hot shower and a flush toilet. 
When we got the water back here and were able to flush the toilets, it lifted 
morale. You didn't have to go to a stinky little outhouse. The little things 
really mean a lot. 
</P>
<P>
 My wife's mother sustained severe damage in Van Nuys. She lost her chimney and 
all her dishes and walls. So, Tuesday night, when I got home, I told my wife's 
sister, "I can't get over to see your mom, but I want you to buy her a whole 
new set of dishes and cups." My wife told me when she walked in and gave her 
that new set of dishes, you would have thought it was a 16-year-old girl 
getting her first kiss. 
</P>
<P>
 When I'm at home, the tremors scare me a lot more. The tremors really belly me 
up at home. I don't like it and I get really scared. But for whatever reason, 
when I'm at work it doesn't hit me that way. I don't know why. I think it's 
because my family's there. When I'm here, everybody's a professional. Everybody 
is trained like me. 
</P>
<P>
 I remember I got heavily involved in the apartment situation. Those people, I 
met them several times in the lobby. They wanted to get their property. The 
people were very upset. I told them, "Here's how you handle this earthquake. 
You got dealt a really bad hand here, but you're alive. No. 2, each day that we 
progress through this shock, things get better." 
</P>
<P>
 I said, "For instance, yesterday you weren't allowed in your apartments. Now, 
today, there is a system in place to allow you into your apartments, so things 
are better already." 
</P>
<P>
 This division will not be back together quickly, but every day it gets better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
